Postsecondary Education Rates in Boston

Loading Data

library(tidyverse, quietly = TRUE, warn.conflicts = FALSE)

library(htmlwidgets, quietly = TRUE, warn.conflicts = FALSE)

library(gstat, quietly = TRUE, warn.conflicts = FALSE)

library(spatial, quietly = TRUE, warn.conflicts = FALSE)
boston_nhoods <- st_read("https://opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/3525b0ee6e6b427f9aab5d0a1d0a1a28_0.kml", quiet = TRUE) %>%
  dplyr::select(Name)

Chloropleth Map

#51.1, 60.2, 45.3, 81.8, 50.3, 72.5, 56.5, 77.9, 18.9, 56.5, 82.1, 22.4, 62.3, 74.3, 88.3, 69.8, 63.6, 64.4, 52.8, 26.4, 15.6, 30.6, 60.6, 60.6, 66.0, 7.9

boston_nhoods <- boston_nhoods %>%
  mutate(ed_rate = c(51.1, 60.2, 45.3, 81.8, 50.3, 72.5, 56.5, 77.9, 18.9, 56.5, 82.1, 22.4, 62.3, 74.3, 88.3, 69.8, 63.6, 64.4, 52.8, 26.4, 15.6, 30.6, 60.6, 60.6, 66.0, 7.9))

boston_nhoods$label <- 
  paste(boston_nhoods$Name, "<br>", 
        boston_nhoods$ed_rate, "percent with Bachelor's Degree or higher") %>% 
  lapply(htmltools::HTML)

bins <- seq(min(boston_nhoods$ed_rate),
            max(boston_nhoods$ed_rate), by = 10)
pal <- colorNumeric("magma", 
                    domain = boston_nhoods$ed_rate,
                    na.color = "#00000000")

leaflet(boston_nhoods) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addPolygons(highlightOptions = highlightOptions(fillOpacity = 1),
              label = ~label,
              fillColor = ~pal(ed_rate),
              weight = 1, color = "black") %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = ~ed_rate,
            bins = 6,
            opacity = 0.7, title = "% of Population<br>Age 25+ With a <br> Bachelor's Degree<br>or Higher",
            position = "topright")

As Points

MA_state_plane <- "+proj=lcc +lat_1=41.71666666666667 +lat_2=42.68333333333333 +lat_0=41 +lon_0=-71.5 +x_0=200000 +y_0=750000 +ellps=GRS80 +units=m +no_defs "

WGS84 <- "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"

nhood_points <- st_centroid(
  st_transform(boston_nhoods, crs = MA_state_plane)) %>%
  st_transform(WGS84)
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(st_transform(boston_nhoods, crs = MA_state_plane)):
## st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over geometries of x
leaflet(nhood_points) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerLite) %>%
  addCircles(label = ~label,
             fillColor = ~pal(ed_rate),
             stroke = FALSE, 
             radius = 200, 
             fillOpacity = 1) %>% 
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = ~ed_rate,
            bins = 3,
            opacity = 0.7, title = "% of Population<br>Age 25+ With a <br> Bachelor's Degree<br>or Higher",
            position = "topright")

  st_transform(MA_state_plane) %>%

Discussion

Of the three representations above I believe that the data-as-points representation is the most appropriate portrayal of the data and the raster interpolation is the least appropriate, despite it being a visually interesting map. I chose to represent percentage data per neighborhood; this is already an average that does not take into account variations within neighborhoods, which could be significant. Portraying the data through centroids is a level of abstraction which forces the viewer to recognize it is aggregate data fo the neighborhood. On the other hand, showing this education data as a continuous surface is misleading - these values are discontinuous.

General trends in the maps show that the closer a neighborhood is to the Cambridge/Downtown Boston/Charles River area of the map, the higher the percentage of the neighborhood’s residents that have bachelor’s degrees or higher. A raster interpolation surface represents this to some extent, but is deceptive because it projects “expected values” that may be very far from reality.

Note

These maps were inspired by a map from a student at the Texas Christian University Center for Urban Studies (http://personal.tcu.edu/kylewalker/maps/education/#12.56/42.3666/-71.1172) and I used 2015 ACS data to aggregate at the neighborhood level.
